    "question_id" : 7924887,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In general, java will not copy objects when you \"add all\", that is, for objects, pointers to the originals are used.</p>\n\n<p><strong>*</strong> But be careful ! For strings, due to immutability, an array copy will not point to the original string values, and you must not expect that changing a pointer to a string that was added to an array list will result in a new value inside the array list. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8104679,
      "reputation" : 1924,
      "user_id" : 6106641,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 80,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/abcf76142302a63f68d274623802104f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Archmede",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6106641/archmede"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1760642526,
    "creation_date" : 1760642526,
    "answer_id" : 79792498,
    "question_id" : 7924887,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Assuming you're asking about <code>ArrayList::addAll</code>; the underlying references of the object will be copied over. Therefore, if an object in the original list is changed, then that object in the new list will also be altered.</p>\n<pre><code>List&lt;MyObject&gt; firstList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\nmyObject.add(new MyObject());\n\nList&lt;MyObject&gt; secondListList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\nsecondList.addAll(firstList);\n\nfirstList.get(0) == secondList.get(0) // true\n</code></pre>\n<p>That being said, the underlying array used as storage in the list is not copied; it's recreated. This means that altering <code>firstList</code> will not alter <code>secondList</code></p>\n<pre><code>//Reusing the same list from the above example\nfirstList.add(new MyObject());\nfirstList.size() == 2; // true\n\nsecondList.size() == 2; // false\nsecondList.size() == 1; // true\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
